description:
perf#18 PHASE D (plan.md §Phase-D) — MINIMAL duplex-ring prototype, ONE scenario only. Do NOT start until Phase C (parent dar-1il.3, the design-only spec) is done and the wake model is re-derived. This is the first time the duplex lane carries a real op.

=== SCENARIO (exactly one) ===
mach_port_deallocate of a MAPPED-REGION-BACKED port — the precise op+shape that wedged the simple ring (dar-1il.1): destroying it drives a vm-munmap S2C upcall to the caller, which a ring-parked (non-recvmsg) caller cannot service => deadlock. This is the canonical caller-S2C case; prove the duplex lane breaks the deadlock class on it before considering any other op.

=== RED / GREEN ===
RED: the SAME operation over the SIMPLE ring deadlocks or is disallowed (it already is — keep a deterministic arm showing the simple lane cannot carry it).
GREEN: the operation over the duplex wait-pump COMPLETES — no deadlock; side effects byte-identical to UDS (type/refs/reclamation/no-garbage/VM cleanup); p50/p99 measured; SIMPLE-RING performance unchanged (mach_reply_port p50 no material regression, simple wake gates still green, control block not bloated).

=== CONSTRAINTS (plan.md §Phase-D — keep it minimal) ===
 - one parent request at a time;
 - one outstanding S2C upcall at first;
 - CALLER-THREAD pump (NOT a helper thread — S2C may need exact caller current_task/current_thread/dtape/TLS context; plan.md §11.2);
 - fallback to UDS on any unexpected shape;
 - NO broad migration, NO general multi-inflight, NO fast-op table, NO change to simple-lane perf.

=== HAZARDS TO COVER (plan.md §11) ===
 - reentrancy: guest may hold a lock L, pump handles upcall, upcall re-takes L -> deadlock (audit common runtime locks);
 - server locks held while waiting for the upcall reply (must not starve other clients / must not wedge the single-threaded loop);
 - cancellation/death: client dies before final reply / after S2C publish / while server waits for upcall reply; server teardown while a duplex parent is pending;
 - ordering vs UDS (parent visibility, nested upcall ordering, final-reply ordering, resource-destruction timing);
 - fast-lane contamination check.

=== POINTERS ===
Depends on dar-1il.3 (Phase-C design) being complete: message types, guest pump semantics, server wait-for-upcall-reply semantics, duplex ABI capability bit/hash, RED->GREEN gate shapes, non-goals. S2C mechanics today: thread.cpp _s2cPerform / _deferReplyForS2C; guest reply-wait dserver-ring.c gr_wait_reply parks on s2c_futex watching only the reply ring (THE problem). HEADs darlingserver @f997803 / xnu @412e15c. plan.md = authoritative. NOTHING PUSHED.

Define and implement the contract for env=darling tests launched through CTest but executed by darling-debug-runner or equivalent wrapper.

Required behavior:
- hard timeout;
- process group/tree cleanup;
- detection of leftover darlingserver/mldr/shellspawn/vchroot/test processes;
- reproducible bundle with command, env, stdout, stderr, exit status, timeout reason, logs, ps/tree snapshot, cleanup result;
- resource locking for tests that mutate a prefix or launchd state;
- forensic capture opt-in only.

Acceptance:
- A deliberately hanging guest smoke test is killed and reported as a normal failed CTest case.
- Bundle contains enough information to replay the exact command.
- Green guest tests do not leave long-lived runtime processes.
- west test documents how diag=bare/guarded/forensic maps to runner behavior.

Prove the workflow by converting representative existing fixes so the test lives with the fix in the same repo/profile instead of relying on a separate testsuite patch.

Initial migration set:
- one xnu/libsystem_kernel contract fix from dar-r7z7 gaps, preferably psynch/getattrlist/fd semantics;
- one darlingserver runtime/RPC/wait fix;
- one top-level darling runtime/build fix;
- one cross-repo/runtime gate where an adjacent test patch in the same profile is more honest than forcing same-patch colocation;
- one E-UNION harness slice promoted from experiments or explicitly documented as an exception if not portable yet.

Acceptance:
- Each migrated patch has committed test files or a same-profile adjacent test patch.
- patches.yml metadata points to each test.
- west test --patch can list and run each migrated proof.
- For each migrated fix, a Bead comment or metadata note records the RED parent/command and GREEN command.
- Migration does not require committing to upstream darling-testsuite.
